**Important Update:**
The new antitarget mechanism will go live at 1:00 PM UTC. Essentially each protein commit will now include two proteins: a target protein and an antitarget protein. The objective for miners is to submit molecules that exhibit high binding affinity to the target protein while having low binding affinity to the antitarget protein. Hello, everyone

We have a big update scheduled to 1PM UTC (soon)! The code is already on main and will start being run by validators at that time.

The big changes introduced in this version are:
- Multitarget competitions: all competitions will be composed of a pair of random targets and anti-targets, meaning that your submission must have high affinity for the target and low affinity for the anti-target. Submissions will be scored with: `score(target) - score(anti-target)`. This number can be negative, but the higher, the better. **No more pains now.**

- Timelocked encryption: submissions will be encrypted using the timelock encryption class written by @Rhef (many thanks 🫶 ). Because the encrypted answer is bigger than the limit of 128 characters for commitment on chain, **the encrypted answer will be uploaded to a PUBLIC github repo that you have pushing rights to** and the data that will be committed to chain is the **path to your submission file within that repo** (see: https://github.com/metanova-labs/nova/blob/main/neurons/miner.py#L39-L51 for the format) , which also must be below 128 characters to be accepted as an commitment on-chain. You must include your repo information in your .env file, for which there is an example on our repo. 

Bear in mind that there is an interval for timelock encryption to be decrypted. This interval is customizable, but if you set it to more than the remaining time of the challenge or submit your answer too close to the end, validators won't be able to decrypt your answer and it will be disregarded.  

To prepare for the update, you may update your environment running the install_deps script suited to your environment + start a new github repo for the competition if you wish to do so. 

Happy molecule hunting 🔎

Suggestion for Using Cloudflare R2 Instead of GitHub Repositories for Protein Submission

I recommend using Cloudflare R2 for protein submissions instead of GitHub repositories. Frequent commits to a repository can trigger account anomalies or even lead to bans.

1. Cloudflare R2 offers better key access control. We can use a public read key to retrieve data, while miners use a write key to submit their data.

2. Encryption concerns are minimal with R2 because the upload timestamp itself serves as a reliable proof of submission.
